5hp.title: 100LDT x 1CDT oneshot PD tournament as arguable counterexample to LDT doing better than CDT
5hp.clickbait: Arguendo, if 100 LDT agents and 1 CDT agent are facing off in a one-shot Prisoner's Dilemma tournament, the CDT agent does better on a problem that CDT considers 'fair'.
5hp.text:
[summary:  As a counterexample to the assertion that [58b LDT] handles a strictly larger [fair_problem_class fair problem class] than [causal_dt CDT], [wei_dai Wei Dai] proposed the example of 100 LDT agents and 100 CDT agents playing each other in a oneshot [prisoners_dilemma Prisoner's Dilemma] without knowledge of the other agent's code.  The LDT agents must cooperate uniformly to avoid accidentally defecting against each other; the CDT agent can defect against all of them.

One might counter that this is no more fair than including a slightly variant algorithm LDT-Prime that thinks it doesn't move in lockstep with LDT, or maybe having a situation where Omega would already have bombed an orphanage two days ago if the LDT agent picked up \$20 bill that the CDT agent then picks up.  But from the standpoint of a CDT agent, certainly, both situations seem quite 'fair' since the CDT agent thinks that the LDT agent would get the same payoff for the same physical act.]

One of the arguments supporting -[58b] over [-causal_dt] is the assertion that [fair_problem_class LDT handles a strictly wider problem class] and therefore [ dominates]:  Arguendo, we lose nothing by moving from CDT to LDT, and instead gain the ability to handle a strictly wider class of problems.  [wei_dai Wei Dai] has offered the following counterexample:  Suppose that 100 LDT agents and 1 CDT agent are playing a tournament of oneshot [prisoners_dilemma].  Then the LDT agents calculate that they will lose a great deal by defecting (since this would make them defect against 100 other LDT agents), while the CDT agent cheerfully defects (and does not move in unison with the LDT agents).

The [fair_problem_class fairness] of this problem isn't entirely beyond dispute, nor that the outcome is favorable to CDT qua decision theory.  For example, we might wonder about inserting a single logical-style agent with some other slightly variant algorithm LDT-Prime such that it no longer sees itself as moving in lockstep with all the other agents.  Then LDT-Prime might do as well as the CDT agent, illustrating that the CDT aspect wasn't the key issue.

If an LDT agent wanted to complain about facing an LDT-Prime or CDT agent being 'unfair', it might complain that by so often facing off against an algorithm moving in logical lockstep with itself, it is being faced with an environmental challenge unlike the LDT-Prime agent or CDT agent.  The LDT agent faces an environment logically correlated with itself while LDT-Prime and CDT don't; so the LDT agent is being presented with different options or consequences for its decision algorithm.

However, the 100LDT x 1CDT scenario seems in some sense *realistic,* and is a challenge to the general statement that the [fair_problem_class fair] problem class on which LDT agents end up rich is strictly larger than the corresponding 'fair' problem class for CDT agents.  That is, a CDT agent might say:  "Why, of course that one-shot PD tournament is fair; nobody is getting a different payoff for the same physical acts."

On the LDT view this is something of a misleading coincidence resulting from the CDT agent's myopic view of the world.  Since the CDT agent is blind to logical correlations, it is possible to set up an unfair test that the CDT agent thinks is fair.  We could, for example, set up some dilemma in which Omega would have bombed an orphanage two days ago, if the LDT algorithm has the logical result of picking up a certain \$20 bill lying in the street.  The CDT agent laughs and remarks that Omega is already gone, and chides the LDT agent for not taking the \$20 reward that it thinks was equally available to any agent passing by.

But on the CDT view, to see a CDT agent happily picking up a clearly present \$20 reward that the superstitious LDT agent refuses to take seems obviously fair.  Similarly, but perhaps much more naturally and convincingly, a CDT agent sees nothing odd about exploiting a hundred irrational LDT agents on a oneshot Prisoner's Dilemma tournament--why, that's exactly what CDT is supposed to be good for.

5n9.title: Causal decision theories
5n9.clickbait: On CDT, to choose rationally, you should imagine the world where your physical act changes, then imagine running that world forward in time.  (Therefore, it's irrational to vote in elections.)

5pt.title: Newcomblike decision problems
5pt.clickbait: Decision problems in which your choice correlates with something other than its physical consequences (say, because somebody has predicted you very well) can do weird things to some decision theories.

5py.title: Prisoner's Dilemma
5py.clickbait: You and an accomplice have been arrested.  Both of you must decide, in isolation, whether to testify against the other prisoner--which subtracts one year from your sentence, and adds two to theirs.

7d6.title: Fair problem class
7d6.clickbait: A problem is 'fair' (according to logical decision theory) when only the results matter and not how we get there.
